**CHAPTER 4: FAKE-OUTS AT MOVING AVERAGES**
Now, here's where most traders completely mess  

58
00:05:17,120 --> 00:05:22,560
up a moving-average trading strategy.
Many assume that if price touches the  

59
00:05:22,560 --> 00:05:30,240
moving-average and bounces once, it will bounce 
forever. That’s not always true. Fake-outs happen  

60
00:05:30,240 --> 00:05:37,920
when price momentarily breaks below or above the 
average, luring YOU in, then flips course again.
  

61
00:05:37,920 --> 00:05:44,160
The market tricks YOU into thinking the trend 
changed. Then it snaps back like a rubber band. 

62
00:05:44,160 --> 00:05:50,960
I personally fell for this trap hundreds of 
times. Price would break below my moving average,  

63
00:05:50,960 --> 00:05:57,920
I'd sell, then it would rocket back up above 
the moving average. Frustrating and expensive!
  

64
00:05:57,920 --> 00:06:05,360
The secret is recognizing fake-out patterns. Real 
breaks have volume and momentum behind them. Fake  

65
00:06:05,360 --> 00:06:12,400
breaks look weak and hesitant. Real breaks 
hold the new level. Fake breaks fail quickly. 

66
00:06:12,400 --> 00:06:16,800
Here's my fake-out filter. When 
price breaks a moving average,  

67
00:06:16,800 --> 00:06:23,440
I wait 15 minutes. If it can't stay on the 
new side with volume, it's probably fake.  

68
00:06:23,440 --> 00:06:30,000
If it creeps back above the moving-average 
within those 15 minutes, I ignore the break.
  

69
00:06:30,000 --> 00:06:35,520
Watch closely here! See how price dipped 
below the moving-average around the market  

70
00:06:35,520 --> 00:06:43,520
open. But no volume. Weak momentum. Within 10 
minutes, it was back above the moving average.  

71
00:06:43,520 --> 00:06:47,920
This is a classic fake-out.
Also check the slope again.  

72
00:06:47,920 --> 00:06:54,000
If the slope is still firmly in your 
favor, that quick breach might be noise.
  

73
00:06:54,000 --> 00:06:58,880
Watch what happens when YOU see a big 
candle that closes under the average,  

74
00:06:58,880 --> 00:07:04,800
but the slope is still pointing up. 
Many times, that move reverses swiftly. 

75
00:07:04,800 --> 00:07:11,120
Here's how YOU implement this. Never trade 
immediately on moving-average breaks. Wait  

76
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:17,120
for confirmation. Watch volume. 
Watch momentum. Watch the slope.  

77
00:07:17,120 --> 00:07:22,960
Let the market prove the break is real.
 
And here’s the best part! Failed fake-outs  

78
00:07:22,960 --> 00:07:28,800
often create the strongest moves in the 
opposite direction. When that fake breakdown  

79
00:07:28,800 --> 00:07:32,640
fails, the bounce can be explosive.
 
**CHAPTER 5: DISPLACED MOVING AVERAGES** 

80
00:07:32,640 --> 00:07:38,320
Most people have never heard of this. A 
displaced moving-average is the same line,  

81
00:07:38,320 --> 00:07:44,480
but shifted to the right on your chart. This 
changes how YOU view price relative to that  

82
00:07:44,480 --> 00:07:50,320
average. If YOU shift it forward, you might 
catch turning points a bit earlier because  

83
00:07:50,320 --> 00:07:56,640
the line doesn’t clutter the present bar. 
 
You see, standard moving averages lag behind  

84
00:07:56,640 --> 00:08:02,000
price. They tell YOU what happened, 
not what's happening now. Displaced  

85
00:08:02,000 --> 00:08:07,200
moving averages solve this problem by 
shifting the line forward in time.
  

86
00:08:07,200 --> 00:08:14,080
This creates something magical. The moving-average 
appears to predict where price wants to go. It's  

87
00:08:14,080 --> 00:08:20,320
not really predicting - it's showing YOU where 
price would be if the current trend continues.
  

88
00:08:20,320 --> 00:08:26,960
Here's where it gets crazy. Price often respects 
these displaced moving averages. The market  

89
00:08:26,960 --> 00:08:34,160
seems to know where these future levels sit.
In this chart I use a 50-period EMA displaced  

90
00:08:34,160 --> 00:08:41,680
forward by 10 periods. This gives me support and 
resistance levels that most traders can't see. 
  

91
00:08:41,680 --> 00:08:47,440
Look at that line ahead of current price! 
That's my displaced moving average. Most  

92
00:08:47,440 --> 00:08:54,000
traders had no idea that level existed.
Here's how YOU implement this. Take your  

93
00:08:54,000 --> 00:09:00,880
favorite moving average. Shift it forward by 
10 of 20 candles, depending on your time frame. 

94
00:09:00,880 --> 00:09:07,120
For example, a 20-period MA gets 
shifted forward 10 periods. Now YOU  

95
00:09:07,120 --> 00:09:10,720
have future support and resistance levels.
 
