137
00:13:22,480 --> 00:13:24,960
**CHAPTER 8: MOVING-AVERAGE RIBBONS**
This part can be a game-changer,  

138
00:13:24,960 --> 00:13:30,640
if used correctly. You’ll be surprised 
how simple a moving-average ribbon can be. 

139
00:13:30,640 --> 00:13:36,800
A ribbon is a set of averages for different 
periods, spaced out. Picture a colorful band  

140
00:13:36,800 --> 00:13:42,400
on your screen. If all lines are stacked 
in order, from shortest to longest,  

141
00:13:42,400 --> 00:13:48,800
that often signals a strong trend. If they 
tangle or flatten, the trend might be weak.
  

142
00:13:48,800 --> 00:13:56,320
So a ribbon is multiple moving averages plotted 
together. Instead of one line, YOU have 8-12  

143
00:13:56,320 --> 00:14:03,120
lines of different periods. When they align, 
they create powerful trend signals. They help  

144
00:14:03,120 --> 00:14:09,120
YOU see the market’s structure at a glance.
Think of it like this. One moving-average  

145
00:14:09,120 --> 00:14:14,480
can lie. Two can be coincidence. 
But when 8-10 moving averages all  

146
00:14:14,480 --> 00:14:20,880
point the same direction, the trend is real.
 
The ribbon works like a traffic light. Green  

147
00:14:20,880 --> 00:14:27,760
when all averages point up and stay separated. 
Red when they point down and stay separated. 

148
00:14:27,760 --> 00:14:34,560
Here's the secret most traders miss. The space 
between the ribbon lines tells YOU trend strength.  

149
00:14:34,560 --> 00:14:42,640
Wide spaces mean strong trends. Narrow spaces 
mean weak trends. Tangled lines mean no trend.
  

150
00:14:42,640 --> 00:14:50,720
For starters, you can use a 12-ribbon system. 
Periods from 5 to 50. When they fan out nicely,  

151
00:14:50,720 --> 00:14:57,520
trade with the trend. When they tangle up, stay 
out. The bigger the separation among the lines,  

152
00:14:57,520 --> 00:15:03,760
the stronger the momentum. If YOU see them 
pinch together, that can mean a slowdown.
  

153
00:15:03,760 --> 00:15:09,680
I used to ignore these. I thought one average 
was enough. But then I realized that a ribbon  

154
00:15:09,680 --> 00:15:16,400
can give me early warnings about trend changes. 
If the fastest average starts to roll over and  

155
00:15:16,400 --> 00:15:21,840
crosses beneath the next line, that’s the 
first sign. If the rest follow, that’s even  

156
00:15:21,840 --> 00:15:28,960
clearer. And the slope of the entire ribbon can 
reveal if the market is accelerating or not. 

157
00:15:28,960 --> 00:15:33,520
The ribbon eliminates a lot of bad 
trades because it keeps YOU out of  

158
00:15:33,520 --> 00:15:40,240
choppy markets. Clean ribbon means clean 
trends. Messy ribbon means messy markets. 

159
00:15:40,240 --> 00:15:44,240
This filter will improve YOUR 
trade selection dramatically. 

160
00:15:44,240 --> 00:15:49,241
Speaking of filters, let me show YOU 
something that works even better...
 
  

161
00:15:49,241 --> 00:15:53,600
**CHAPTER 9: MOVING-AVERAGE ENVELOPES**
99% of traders have never heard of envelopes, but  

162
00:15:53,600 --> 00:16:00,480
they're game-changers for moving-average traders.
Envelopes are bands drawn above and below a  

163
00:16:00,480 --> 00:16:09,600
moving average. Usually 2-3% above and below. They 
create channels that contain most price movement.
  

164
00:16:09,600 --> 00:16:16,320
When price hits the upper envelope, it often 
reverses down. When it hits the lower envelope,  

165
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:22,560
it often reverses up. The moving-average 
in the middle acts as the balance point. 

166
00:16:22,560 --> 00:16:30,000
So envelopes expand or contract based on a 
percentage or volatility measure around a single  

167
00:16:30,000 --> 00:16:37,680
moving average. This helps YOU see potential 
overbought or oversold conditions in real time. 

168
00:16:37,680 --> 00:16:45,280
And this is exactly why envelopes work better than 
other indicators. They adapt to market volatility  

169
00:16:45,280 --> 00:16:53,040
automatically. In quiet markets, the bands 
are tight. In volatile markets, they expand.
  

170
00:16:53,040 --> 00:16:57,520
Envelopes work most of the time 
because they move with the market. 

171
00:16:57,520 --> 00:17:05,120
The beauty of envelopes is mean reversion. Price 
rarely stays at extreme levels long. It wants to  

172
00:17:05,120 --> 00:17:10,800
return to the average. The envelopes 
show YOU where extreme levels are.
  

173
00:17:10,800 --> 00:17:16,720
Take a look at this. See how price bounced 
perfectly between the envelope bands. Upper  

174
00:17:16,720 --> 00:17:23,680
band rejections led to profitable shorts. 
Lower band bounces led to profitable longs.
  

175
00:17:23,680 --> 00:17:29,440
Now, don’t think envelopes are only for 
sideways markets. Actually, a trending  

176
00:17:29,440 --> 00:17:36,400
market can also ride the upper envelope band. 
If YOU see price clinging to the top band, that  

177
00:17:36,400 --> 00:17:44,000
might signal strong momentum. If price wanders 
inside the envelope, momentum may be fading.
  

178
00:17:44,000 --> 00:17:51,360
Here's how YOU implement this. Set a percentage 
offset around your 20 or 50 moving average. Maybe  

179
00:17:51,360 --> 00:17:59,760
2% or 3%. Watch how price interacts with those 
boundaries. When price hits the upper envelope,  

180
00:17:59,760 --> 00:18:06,000
look for short setups. When it hits the 
lower envelope, look for long setups. 

181
00:18:06,000 --> 00:18:10,514
This concept gets even more 
powerful when we add volume.
 

182
00:18:10,514 --> 00:18:13,280
**CHAPTER 10: VOLUME-WEIGHTED MOVING AVERAGE**
If YOU only look at price, YOU might miss a  

183
00:18:13,280 --> 00:18:18,240
piece of the puzzle. You see, regular 
moving averages treat every price point  

184
00:18:18,240 --> 00:18:23,920
equally. A big volume day has the 
same weight as low volume day. This  

185
00:18:23,920 --> 00:18:28,720
creates problems because volume 
shows institutional interest.
  

186
00:18:28,720 --> 00:18:34,960
Volume-weighted moving averages solve this 
by giving more weight to high-volume periods.  

187
00:18:34,960 --> 00:18:40,560
When institutions trade heavily, those 
prices get more influence on the average. 

188
00:18:40,560 --> 00:18:47,440
Think of it like voting. Regular moving averages 
give everyone one vote. Volume-weighted averages  

189
00:18:47,440 --> 00:18:54,480
give bigger traders more votes. Since bigger 
traders move markets, this makes sense.
  

190
00:18:54,480 --> 00:19:00,480
The volume-weighted average reacts faster 
to price changes when volume is high. It  

191
00:19:00,480 --> 00:19:07,600
reacts slower when volume is low. This creates 
more accurate support and resistance levels. 

192
00:19:07,600 --> 00:19:13,840
Here's where it gets interesting. Price often 
respects volume-weighted average levels better  

193
00:19:13,840 --> 00:19:20,240
than regular moving averages. Because these 
are lines where the real money changed hands.
  

194
00:19:20,240 --> 00:19:25,760
I started using volume-weighted lines 
for scalping, after noticing my regular  

195
00:19:25,760 --> 00:19:32,000
EMAs were giving too many false signals. The 
volume-weighted lines kept me in good trades  

196
00:19:32,000 --> 00:19:39,680
longer and got me out of bad trades faster.
Watch closely here. Compare a regular 20-period  

197
00:19:39,680 --> 00:19:46,000
average with a 20-period volume-weighted average.
Observe how the volume line hugs  

198
00:19:46,000 --> 00:19:49,440
price action better.
The volume-weighted line  

199
00:19:49,440 --> 00:19:56,030
works especially well during breakouts. That’s 
because breakouts need volume to sustain. 
 

200
00:19:56,030 --> 00:19:59,200
**CHAPTER 11: MULTIPLE TIMEFRAME MOVING AVERAGES**
Now, here's where most traders completely mess  

201
00:19:59,200 --> 00:20:03,840
up their moving-average strategies 
- they only look at one timeframe. 

202
00:20:03,840 --> 00:20:09,920
That’s a missed opportunity. If YOU track a 
daily average, and then an intraday average,  

203
00:20:09,920 --> 00:20:16,240
YOU can align your trades with the bigger trend.
 
If the higher timeframe average is bullish,  

204
00:20:16,240 --> 00:20:21,520
but your lower timeframe average turns 
bearish, maybe YOU only take short-term  

205
00:20:21,520 --> 00:20:28,160
quick trades. Or skip the short side entirely.
The daily chart average shows the big picture  

206
00:20:28,160 --> 00:20:35,680
trend. The 1-hour chart shows entry timing.
When all timeframes align, trades work better.  

207
00:20:35,680 --> 00:20:42,240
When they conflict, you will struggle. This 
is why YOU need multiple timeframe analysis.
  

208
00:20:42,240 --> 00:20:48,160
Here's my timeframe system. Daily chart 
for trend direction. 1-hour chart for  

209
00:20:48,160 --> 00:20:56,400
entry timing. Both must agree before I risk money.
I use a 10-period simple moving-average on daily  

210
00:20:56,400 --> 00:21:01,040
and 20-period on the hourly one. 
 
You might say, “I don’t want to  

211
00:21:01,040 --> 00:21:07,680
juggle multiple charts.” But it’s worth it.
Last week I took a long trade on the hourly chart,  

212
00:21:07,680 --> 00:21:14,880
not realizing the daily average was sloping 
downward. That daily line crushed my trade. 
  

213
00:21:14,880 --> 00:21:20,560
Here’s how YOU do it. Check a lower period 
average on a higher time frame. Price  

214
00:21:20,560 --> 00:21:26,480
above it? Is it sloping up? That means 
the long-term trend might be strong. 

215
00:21:26,480 --> 00:21:33,920
Now see a higher period average, on a lower chart. 
If that’s also bullish, that’s more confirmation. 

216
00:21:33,920 --> 00:21:39,280
And never trade when timeframes disagree.
This filter alone will improve  

217
00:21:39,280 --> 00:21:42,800
YOUR win rate by 20-30%. 
 
**CHAPTER 12: MOVING-AVERAGE REVERSION TRADES** 

218
00:21:42,800 --> 00:21:48,960
Now, most traders think moving averages 
are only for trend following. Not really,  

219
00:21:48,960 --> 00:21:53,760
they're equally powerful for mean 
reversion in the right conditions. 

220
00:21:53,760 --> 00:21:59,600
Mean reversion means price returns to 
average after extreme moves. When price  

221
00:21:59,600 --> 00:22:05,360
gets too far from a moving average, it 
usually snaps back like a rubber band.
  

222
00:22:05,360 --> 00:22:11,120
You’ll be surprised how simple this reversion 
plan can be. It might be dangerous if the  

223
00:22:11,120 --> 00:22:18,000
trend is super strong, but in a range or mild 
trend, a reversion can bring quick profits. 

224
00:22:18,000 --> 00:22:23,440
I used to ignore reversion trades. Then 
I realized that markets rarely move in a  

225
00:22:23,440 --> 00:22:30,880
straight line. Even in a robust uptrend, price 
might get overheated and revert to the line. 
 
  

226
00:22:30,880 --> 00:22:35,040
If YOU see that price is extremely 
distant from the average, that can  

227
00:22:35,040 --> 00:22:41,040
be a short-term fade opportunity. Just 
watch for slope. If slope is steeply up,  

228
00:22:41,040 --> 00:22:48,320
it might be risky to fade. But if slope is 
gentle or flat, a reversion trade can work.
  

229
00:22:48,320 --> 00:22:55,120
The key is identifying when price has moved 
too far. I use a simple rule. If price is  

230
00:22:55,120 --> 00:23:03,840
more than 3% away from the 200-period EMA, it's 
extended. Extended price often reverts quickly. 

231
00:23:03,840 --> 00:23:10,800
I enter only if I see a divergence at the top or 
bottom of the channel. Or if I see a trendline  

232
00:23:10,800 --> 00:23:18,160
breakout. That are my confirmation filters.
 
Look at this trade. Observe how price gapped  

233
00:23:18,160 --> 00:23:26,720
down 4% below the 200 EMA. That long trade was a 
good candidate for reversion setup. Price was back  

234
00:23:26,720 --> 00:23:35,520
at the EMA by the next day. Easy 100 pip profit.
 
So here's how YOU implement this. Use envelopes,  

235
00:23:35,520 --> 00:23:42,320
or another reversion channel. When price moves 
more than 3% away from YOUR moving average,  

236
00:23:42,320 --> 00:23:48,240
look for reversion trades back to the 
average. Enter on the first sign of reversal,  

237
00:23:48,240 --> 00:23:54,600
after a divergence, or a trendline breakout. 
And simply target the moving average.
  

238
00:23:54,600 --> 00:23:57,680
**CHAPTER 13: ADAPTIVE MOVING AVERAGES**
Now very important, most traders pick a  

239
00:23:57,680 --> 00:24:05,120
fixed period. For example, they use a 50 period 
average no matter the conditions. But an adaptive  

240
00:24:05,120 --> 00:24:10,720
moving-average adjusts its calculation 
based on market volatility or price  

241
00:24:10,720 --> 00:24:17,600
behavior. That helps YOU respond better 
if conditions shift from quiet to wild.
  

242
00:24:17,600 --> 00:24:25,040
You see, regular moving averages never adjust to 
market conditions. Adaptive moving averages change  

243
00:24:25,040 --> 00:24:30,960
their sensitivity based on market volatility.
When markets are trending strongly,  

244
00:24:30,960 --> 00:24:37,360
adaptive moving averages speed up to follow 
the trend closely. When markets turn choppy,  

245
00:24:37,360 --> 00:24:42,400
they slow down to filter out noise.
Think of it like cruise control that  

246
00:24:42,400 --> 00:24:46,800
adjusts to road conditions. 
 
The most popular adaptive  

247
00:24:46,800 --> 00:24:52,880
moving-average is the Kaufman one. It uses 
an efficiency ratio to determine how much  

248
00:24:52,880 --> 00:25:00,400
to adapt. High efficiency means trending 
market. Low efficiency means choppy market. 

249
00:25:00,400 --> 00:25:07,440
The result is a line that’s dynamic, not 
static. It might hug price closer when things  

250
00:25:07,440 --> 00:25:14,480
get crazy and drift away when things settle.
 
Here's why this matters for YOUR moving-average  

251
00:25:14,480 --> 00:25:20,960
strategy. Fixed period moving averages give 
false signals in changing conditions. But  

252
00:25:20,960 --> 00:25:28,080
adaptive moving averages adjust automatically.
I discovered Kaufman adaptive moving-average a  

253
00:25:28,080 --> 00:25:35,600
few years ago, after getting whipsawed repeatedly 
during market transitions. My regular EMAs kept  

254
00:25:35,600 --> 00:25:42,480
giving false signals. The back test showed that 
the adaptive average stayed smooth and reliable.
  

255
00:25:42,480 --> 00:25:50,320
Compare the regular 20 EMA with a 20-period 
adaptive average during trends and choppy period.  

256
00:25:50,320 --> 00:25:55,200
See how the adaptive average speeds 
up to follow the trend closely.  

257
00:25:55,200 --> 00:26:01,920
Then it slows down to filter out noise
And a bonus tip: the adaptive average works  

258
00:26:01,920 --> 00:26:09,321
especially well during news events and during the 
market open, when volatility changes rapidly.
 
 
 
  

259
00:26:09,321 --> 00:26:11,600
**CHAPTER 14: MOVING-AVERAGE CLUSTERS**
Most people miss this completely,  

260
00:26:11,600 --> 00:26:18,240
but moving-average clusters create the strongest 
support and resistance levels YOU'll ever see. 

261
00:26:18,240 --> 00:26:23,040
A cluster happens when multiple moving 
averages converge at the same price  

262
00:26:23,040 --> 00:26:29,680
level. Instead of one moving average, 
YOU have 2 or lines all sitting together. 

263
00:26:29,680 --> 00:26:35,200
If YOU see the 20, 50, and 100 
averages all near the same price,  

264
00:26:35,200 --> 00:26:42,560
that can be a magnet for the market. Price 
might stall there, bounce, or break with force.
  

265
00:26:42,560 --> 00:26:47,840
Here's why clusters work so well. Each 
moving-average represents a different  

266
00:26:47,840 --> 00:26:52,880
group of traders. The 20-period 
represents short-term traders.  

267
00:26:52,880 --> 00:27:00,480
The 50-period represents medium-term traders. 
The 200-period represents long-term traders. 

268
00:27:00,480 --> 00:27:04,400
When all these groups agree on a 
price level, that level becomes  

269
00:27:04,400 --> 00:27:11,360
incredibly important. Bounces are sharp. 
Breakouts are violent. No middle ground.
  

270
00:27:11,360 --> 00:27:16,960
I hunt for clusters every morning before 
the market opens. They show me exactly  

271
00:27:16,960 --> 00:27:23,920
where the big moves will happen that day.
Check this out! Observe how the 20, 50,  

272
00:27:23,920 --> 00:27:30,480
and 100-period moving averages all converged 
around this area. Well, price bounced over  

273
00:27:30,480 --> 00:27:36,800
100 pips off that cluster level.
The plan is simple: if price bounces  

274
00:27:36,800 --> 00:27:42,880
off a cluster, trade the bounce direction. If 
price breaks through a cluster with volume,  

275
00:27:42,880 --> 00:27:47,680
trade the breakout direction.
 
YOU now have many angles to refine  

276
00:27:47,680 --> 00:27:53,840
your own moving-average trading strategy.
Use each chapter’s insights in a way that  

277
00:27:53,840 --> 00:27:54,674
fits YOU. If YOU like quick scalping trades, 
check slope changes or the bounce pattern. 

278
00:27:54,674 --> 00:27:54,748
If YOU prefer a big-picture method, 
try multiple timeframes or envelopes. 

279
00:27:54,748 --> 00:27:54,800
If YOU love nuance, add 
adaptive lines or clusters. 

280
00:27:54,800 --> 00:27:55,035
And remember what I showed YOU 
about fake-outs and crossovers. 

281
00:27:55,035 --> 00:27:55,680
Now, if you're curious about 
mastering more techniques, go ahead  

282
00:27:56,640 --> 00:28:06,000
and watch one of these videos next!

